Section 2

Identify 5 best ad groups

Considering Total Revenue and a new metric, Profit, to find the best performaing ad groups.

We will use the aggregated data to compute Profit for each ad group, given by below equation.

\(Profit = Total\ revenue - (Avg.\ cost\ per\ click\ *\ No.\ of\ ads\ clicked)\)

# Order data frame by Revenue in descending order and select top 5 ad groups.
copy_at2 = copy_at1[order(copy_at1$total_revenue, decreasing = T), ]
df2 = subset(copy_at2, select = c(ad_group, total_revenue))
df2 = df2[1:5, ]
gb = ggplot(df2, aes(x = reorder(ad_group, -total_revenue), y = total_revenue)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', fill="lightblue") + 
    theme_minimal() + 
    labs(title="Top 5 ad groups by Total Revenue", x="Ad group", y = "Total revenue (USD)")
gb

# Calculate Profit and order in descending order to select top 5 ad groups.
copy_at2$profit = copy_at2$total_revenue-(copy_at2$avg_cost_per_click * copy_at2$clicked)
copy_at2 = copy_at2[order(copy_at2$profit, decreasing = T), ]
df3 = subset(copy_at2, select = c(ad_group, profit))
df3 = df3[1:5, ]
gc = ggplot(df3, aes(x = reorder(ad_group, -profit), y = profit)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', fill="lightblue") +
    theme_minimal() + 
    labs(title="Top 5 ad groups by Profit/Loss", x="Ad group", y = "Profit/Loss (USD)")
gc

  • Through the above two charts we can see that there are two different perspectives, i.e.if only the Total Revenue is considered then the top 5 ad groups in decreasing order of revenue are: 13, 18, 4, 20 and 26 respectively.
  • Selecting only the Revenue as the deciding factor does not tell us the Profit or Net Income after expenses.
  • So we calculate the Profit by factoring the amount spent on advertising, and it gives a completely different result. The profits are negative i.e.loss and by ordering the loss as decreasing, the top 5 ad groups in increasing order of profit/loss are: 9, 31, 14, 27 and 21 respectively.
  • This gives us some insight that the ad groups which have th highest revenues are not the highest in terms of profit also. And they have a low conversion rate and/or the avg. click cost is high which reduces the final profit.

Section 3.2

There are a few time instances in the above chart when the view is 0 for certain ad groups.
This could be either due to missing data in shown or missing dates.
First we will find the ad groups with missing dates and add back missing dates, these rows will have shown set to 0.
We will then impute the zero values in shown by the average views for a particular ad group. This will help to avoid any problems with time-series modeling.

# Find the ad groups and their indices where views are zero
copy_at4 = subset(ad_table, select = c(date, shown, ad_group))

# Find dates
ad_list = unique(copy_at4$ad_group)
prev_dates = 0
mis_grps = c()
for(ad in ad_list) {
  dates = length(copy_at4[copy_at4$ad_group == ad, "date"])
  if(dates < prev_dates) {
    mis_grps = c(mis_grps, ad)
  }
  prev_dates = dates
}
cat("\nAd groups with missing dates are -", mis_grps)
## 
## Ad groups with missing dates are - 10 14 18 20 24
# Setup a default list of dates
def_dates = as.Date(copy_at4[copy_at4$ad_group == 1, "date"])
# Get the groups with missing dates
# Find the missing date (these groups are only missing one date)
# Insert the missing date
for(mis in mis_grps) {
  mis_dates = as.Date(copy_at4[copy_at4$ad_group == mis, "date"])
  mdate = as.Date(setdiff(def_dates, mis_dates), origin = "1970-01-01")
  ins_df = data.frame(date = mdate, shown = 0, ad_group = mis)
  copy_at4 = rbind(copy_at4, ins_df)
}

# Order by ad and date
copy_at4 = copy_at4[order(copy_at4[,3], copy_at4[,1] ), ]

# Fix ads shown
zero_list = copy_at4[copy_at4$shown == 0, "ad_group"]
index_list = which(copy_at4$shown == 0)
cat("\nNo. of zero views originally:", length(zero_list))
## 
## No. of zero views originally: 18
# Impute the zero views with avg. views for each ad group
# If an ad group is repeated, use a single avg. value to impute
counter = 1
prev_ad = 0
prev_impt = 0
for(ad in zero_list) {
  if(ad == prev_ad) {
    copy_at4$shown[index_list[counter]] = prev_impt
  }
  else {
    views = copy_at4[copy_at4$ad_group == ad, "shown"]
    prev_impt = round(mean(views))
    copy_at4$shown[index_list[counter]] = prev_impt
    prev_ad = ad
  }
  counter = counter + 1
}

zero_list = copy_at4[copy_at4$shown == 0, "ad_group"]
cat("\nNo. of zero views after imputation:", length(zero_list))
## 
## No. of zero views after imputation: 0
# Visualize the changes
df5 = melt(copy_at4, id.vars="date", measure.vars="shown", variable.name = "ad_group")
df5$ad_group = as.character(copy_at4$ad_group)

ge = ggplot(df5, aes(x=date, y=value, colour=ad_group, group=ad_group)) +
    geom_line() +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(title="Ad Views", x="Time", y = "Views")

Section 3.3

Perform stationarity test

We have to analyze if the time-series satifies the stationarity critera for forecasting purposes.
We will calculate a 7-day/weekly moving average of the no. of ad views to smoothen the data first.

library(forecast)
library(tseries)
copy_at5 = copy_at4
copy_at5$date = as.Date(copy_at5$date)

# Since there is data only for about 2 months, we will calculate a weekly moving average
ad_list = unique(copy_at4$ad_group)
copy_at5$shown_ma = NA
for(ad in ad_list) {
  copy_at5[copy_at5$ad_group == ad, "shown_ma"] = ma(copy_at5[copy_at5$ad_group == ad, "shown"], order=7)
}

cat("No. of missing values in moving avg.-", sum(is.na(copy_at5$shown_ma)))
## No. of missing values in moving avg.- 240
# Round the MAs
copy_at5$shown_ma = round(copy_at5$shown_ma)

# Visualize the changes
df6 = melt(copy_at5, id.vars="date", measure.vars="shown_ma", variable.name = "ad_group")
df6$ad_group = as.character(copy_at5$ad_group)

gf = ggplot(df6, aes(x=date, y=value, colour=ad_group, group=ad_group)) +
    geom_line() +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(title="Ad Views", x="Time", y = "MA Views")
gf

# Stationarity test (Augmented Dickey-Fuller test)
# Print only if not stationary
for(ad in ad_list) {
  shown_ma = ts(na.omit(copy_at5[copy_at5$ad_group == ad, "shown_ma"]), frequency=7)
  adf_test = adf.test(shown_ma, alternative = "stationary")
  if (adf_test[3] != "stationary") {
    cat("\n ADF Test result for ad group-", ad, "is not stationary")
  }
}

Section 3.4

Fit ARIMA model for forecasting

Fit the model using the calculated moving average.

# Define starting week and day since for the weekly frequency
start_w = as.numeric(strftime(copy_at5[4, "date"], format = "%W"))
start_d = as.numeric(strftime(copy_at5[4, "date"], format = "%w"))

fcast_df = data.frame(ad_group=NA, fcast_shown=NA)
for(ad in ad_list) {
  shown_ma = ts(na.omit(copy_at5[copy_at5$ad_group == ad, "shown_ma"]), start=c(start_w, start_d), frequency=7)
  shown_dec = stl(shown_ma, s.window="periodic")
  shown_desnl = seasadj(shown_dec)
  fit = auto.arima(shown_desnl, seasonal=FALSE)
  # tsdisplay(residuals(fit), lag.max=45, main='(1,1,1) Model Residuals')
  # ACF and PACF plots for the 40 ad groups suggest that auto-fitted model is sufficient
  fcast <- forecast(fit, h=41) # December 15
  # Visualize the forecast
  # title = paste0("Forecast for ad group-", ad)
  # plot(fcast, ylab = "Ads shown (predicted)", main = title)
  temp_df = data.frame(ad_group=ad, fcast_shown=round(fcast$mean[1]))
  fcast_df = rbind(fcast_df, temp_df) 
}
cat("The forecasted number of ads thay may be shown on December 15\n")
## The forecasted number of ads thay may be shown on December 15
fcast_df = na.omit(fcast_df)
fcast_df

Section 4.4

Based on trends group data into up, down and flat categories

We add an additional 4th category called Mixed if the trend is not clear.
We will use the moving average to find the trend in each ad group.

direction = function(x) {
  upt = length(which(diff(x) > 0))
  dwnt = length(which(diff(x) < 0))
  fltt = length(which(diff(x) == 0))
  # If 65% of data is in a particular direction then set the trend
  if(upt >= 26)
    return("Upward")
  else if(dwnt >= 26)
    return("Downward")
  else if(fltt >= 26)   
    return("Flat")
  else if(upt == dwnt)  # If up and down are equal then consider as flat
    return("Flat")
  else
    return("Mixed")
}

trend_df = data.frame(ad_group=NA, trend=NA)
for(ad in ad_list) {
  # The moving average smoothed the data such that there is no clear trend
  # Most groups are falling under the Mixed category
  # trend = direction(copy_at6[copy_at6$ad_group == ad, "cost_ma"])
  
  # Using the original click cost
  trend = direction(copy_at6[copy_at6$ad_group == ad, "avg_cost_per_click"])
  trend_df[ad, ] = c(ad, trend)
}
trend_df = na.omit(trend_df)

trend_list = c("Upward", "Downward", "Flat", "Mixed")
cat("\nThe ad groups with the four click cost trends are given below\n")
## 
## The ad groups with the four click cost trends are given below
for(trend in trend_list) {
  cat(trend, "-", trend_df[trend_df$trend == trend, "ad_group"], "\n")
}

  • Using the avg_cost_per_click helped us to obtain more clear trends.
